Why the existing system doesn’t work
Second, how do we solve it.
The modern refugee system was developed after World War II.
It was intended to make sure that when a country collapses or worse, the regime is hostile to the people of that country, and that people can have a place to go where they live in safety and dignity until they can return to their homeland.
Just like what we see in Syria today.
Through an international conference signed by 147 governments, the 1951 Convention on the Status of Refugees and an international organization, the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR), has committed itself to allowing people from other countries to enter their territories from conflict and persecution.
But now the system is collapsing.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek asylum.
In reality, our immigration policy is blocking the path to security.
In theory, refugees have the right to seek equal treatment or to choose to return to their home countries.
But in practice, they're trapped in a state of stagnation that is almost indefinite.
In theory, the refugee problem is the responsibility of all countries.
In practice, geographic location means that countries close to conflict are overloaded with the vast majority of refugees.
The rules of the original refugee system are not the cause of its collapse.
But we're not using enough as the world changes, and that's something we need to rethink.
So I want to explain to you how the current system works.
How does the current refugee reception system work?
But not from a top-down macroscopic perspective, but from an individual refugee perspective.
Imagine a Syrian woman.
