All the pathways we take for granted access to the global economy can and should be made available to refugees.
The second idea I want to discuss is the economic zone.
Unfortunately, not all of the world's host countries have adopted Uganda's policies.
Most of the host country's economy is not open to refugees, but we still have effective alternatives.
Last April I went to Jordan, and I went to Jordan, with my colleague Paul Kolya, the development economist, and we discussed an idea there, with the international community and the local government, that was to bring jobs to Syrians and to advance Jordan's national development strategy.
The idea is to create an economic zone where we can combine the employment of refugees with the national employment in the host country, Jordan.
Just a 15-minute drive outside Zatali camp, where 83,000 refugees are resettled here is an existing economic zone known as King Hussein Development Zone.
