So what if the refugees could work there instead of being stuck in a refugee camp and be able to afford the house before they return to Syria and develop their skills through vocational training?
We recognize that doing so would benefit Jordan, and its national development strategy requires upgrading the manufacturing industry as a middle-income country.
This will benefit the refugees and also help the post-war reconstruction of Syria by recognizing that we need to train refugees as the best resource for the eventual reconstruction of Syria.
We published this in the journal Foreign Affairs.
Jordan's King Abdullah also adopted the idea.
Two weeks ago, at the Syrian conference in London, the pilot project will begin this summer.
