You may have never heard of Kenema in Sierra Leone, or Aroua of Nigeria.
But I think they are two of the best places in the world.
The hospital there, a community of nurses, surgeons and scientists, has been quietly battling one of humanity’s deadliest threats for years – the Lhasa virus.
The Lhasa virus is very much like Ebola.
It can cause severe fever symptoms and is often fatal.
But these people risk their lives every day to protect every member of the community, and at the same time, to protect all of us.
The best thing I learned from them was that when I first visited many years ago, those challenging, front-line days, they started every morning -- singing.
They gather together to show their joy.
They show a spirit.
Many years have passed, and when we visit each other year after year, I can get together to sing with them, and we'll record that, and we love to do that, because it reminds us that we're not just going to search for the truth of science together, but a human bond that binds us together.
And you can imagine that when the surroundings change, this connection becomes extremely important, even indispensable.
In March 2014, a major change occurred. The Ebola outbreak broke out in Guinea.
This is the first outbreak in the West African region, at the border between Sierra Leone and Libya.
The situation was terrible and we were all shocked.
In fact, we even suspected that Lhasa and the Ebola epidemic were spreading more widely than we thought, and we feared that one day it would spread to Kenema.
So my team immediately set out, got there, and joined Dr. Humar Khan and his team, and we built diagnostic equipment to do some sensitive molecular testing, and we could detect Ebola when it crossed the Sierra Leone border.
We've already set up devices of this scale for the Lhasa virus , and we know how to deal with it, and the team is fantastic.
We just need to give them equipment and space to study Ebola.
Unfortunately, that day has come.
On May 23, 2014, a woman was admitted to a delivery room in a hospital, and our team conducted those important molecular tests and confirmed the first case of Ebola in Sierra Leone.
This is actually very great.
They can diagnose the condition at the first time, treat the patient safely, and start tracking contacts to follow the spread of the disease.
It could have stopped something.
But by the time that day came, the outbreak had been brewing for months.
After hundreds of cases were detected, it dwarfed all previous outbreaks.
And the virus didn't come to Sierra Leone by that single case, it's a huge shockwave.
We had to work closely with the international community, with the Ministry of Health, with Kenema, to deal with these cases. The next week came 31 patients, then 92, then up to 147 -- all flocked to Kenema, because this is one of the few places in Sierra Leone that can respond to the epidemic.
We worked day and night, trying to help every patient, hoping to get everyone's attention, but we also did another simple thing.
To detect Ebola, we took samples from the patient's blood, and we could, of course, throw them away.
But the fact that the other thing we can do is add chemicals to the sample to inactivate, and then seal it in a box and transport it across the ocean, and that's what we do.
We sent the sample to Boston, where my team worked.
We worked day and night, working every day, so we quickly sorted out 99 genomes of Ebola.
That's a blueprint -- the genome of a virus is a blueprint.
We humans have too.
It details everything that makes up our bodies and tells us a lot of information.
The results of these efforts are simple, but powerful.
We can take these 99 different virus variants, look at and compare them, and we can see clearly that compared to the three genomes released by Guinea, we can find that the disease has been circulating in Guinea a few months ago, and once it breaks into the population, it will be transmitted quickly through human-to-human contact.
This information is really important, especially when you're looking at how to stop the spread of the virus, but the most important thing is contact tracing.
We can also see that when the virus is spreading from person to person, it is constantly mutating.
Every variation is incredibly important because all the diagnoses, the vaccines, and the treatments we use are basically based on that specific genome sequence, which is the root cause of the spread of the epidemic.
So health professionals around the world need to respond quickly, improve research methods, and adjust everything they do.
But in my position at the time, the way I was in the scientific research was that I got the data, and I might have to shut up in the lab for months, carefully and carefully analyzed the data, wrote the papers, and then made them revised, and finally the papers were made public.
This is the current state of scientific research at that time.
Well, at that particular time that approach certainly doesn't work, does it?
Some of our friends work on the front line of the disease, and obviously the most important thing for us is outside help, a lot of help.
So the first thing we did, the genetic sequencing came out of the machine, and we immediately posted the data online.
We open it to the whole world and say, “Help us!”
Then help to follow.
We didn’t react, and there was a large group of people around the world who took the initiative to contact us, and they were pleasantly surprised to see that the data was available online.
Some of the best virus trackers in the world have suddenly become part of our team!
We work together in this virtual way, we share information, we talk to each other on the phone, keep in touch, and hopefully track the spread of the virus in seconds and find a way to contain it.
There are many ways to form such a group.
Everyone, especially when the epidemic is worldwide, is constantly getting information, participating in it, and investing in it.
Everyone wants to make a contribution.
The power of all the people in the world is really amazing, and the Internet connects us.
We’re no longer afraid to communicate with others, and we all say, “Get started.”
Let’s work together, we can do it!”
But the problem is that the data that we all use, the data we find on Google, is far from meeting the needs of our work.
When that happens, we miss a lot of opportunities.
So in the early days of Kenema, we had 106 clinical records of patients, and we made them public once again.
In our own lab, you give us the 106 records, and we can get the computer to predict the next Ebola patient, and the accuracy is close to 100 percent.
